making paper things… is definitely one of my favourite things.

Supplies:
+cord of choice.
+watercolor paper or sturdy card stock in color of choice.
+shape outline or shape punch
+light wire.
+hole punch 
+scissors.
+wire cutters.
+ruler.
+optional: cutting machine. (like the @cricut)
.
The Steps:
1. cut your desired shapes.
2. cut your cord to desired length.
3. tie a loop at one end.
4. tie loose knots approximately every 5 Inches down the cord.
5. tie another loop at the end.
6. cut wire in 3” lengths to attach your shape. the wire allows the shapes to dangle a bit. (which I love). Alternatively you could simply tie the shapes directly to your cord. 
7. Hang and enjoy.

making rag ball ribbon or is it ribbon rag balls….
.

once upon a time I was a crafter. I even went to craft sales.  which thinking back on that … I can’t believe I did that.  Being the introvert that I am. .
:) Anyhow, as crafter do… I collected a lot of lovely supplies. Including the most beautiful homespun fabrics. . this homespun was my favourite.  the Meme’s Quilt collection.  (which I just googled only to discover it’s considered vintage now? what the heck?) . one of the lovely things about homespun is the loose weave. I love how it tears with ease both ways.
muslin is similar as well.
.
anyhow… I love tearing this into strips for added touches to gifts.
.
often I’ll wrap the strips around wooden spools… which is so pretty.
but today… I decided to make some ribbon rag balls. or rag ball ribbon?
. .
rag balls look lovely in bowls around the holiday as well. .
. 
If you wanna elevate the whole experience mix your fabric strip on the ball… kinda like a secret surprise waiting inside the rag ball as you use up the ribbon on the roll. .
.
Supplies. styrofoam balls a decorative tack or pin. and strips of fabric.
.
I used upholstery tacks (also left over from my crafting days)
one to secure the first piece to the styrofoam ball. and one more to secure the end. pins would work beautifully as well. . if gifting….a ribbon rag ball…
you could attach a little paper note to the styrofoam ball. ie.
you are amazing. or hello lovely. ♡  for your friend or loved one to discover at the end of the ‘roll’. .

I’ve been deep in “the Mac zone” for what feels like months, pouring my heart into the Momentum Method program, lotsa zoom calls with the most amazing 1:1’s  and juggling a few side projects as well.  . My camera and I were overdue for some quality time together. . It’s easy to get swept up in life’s busy-ness and forget to pause and appreciate the simple, beautiful things that were once a dream. Like the studio I get to come to each day. . It started as a vision in my mind, with lofty ceilings and beams, white walls, massive windows, and props everywhere.  As I imagined this space, I thought we’d need to build it from scratch, but little did I know, it already existed as the antique shop downtown, concealed by countless walls and dark wood. .
Maybe that’s how we are too—our truest selves hidden beneath layers of stories and years, patiently waiting for us to take one step forward and then another, gradually allowing our most true self to shine through. .
Hold on, how did this caption begin?  Oh right, I just wanted to share my blissful Friday spent with my camera. But apparently, these are the thoughts swirling in my mind today.
.
.
Anyone care to share something that was once just a dream? and is now true. . I’d love, love to hear. . and hello Monday. let’s do this well. xxxxx .

I must share the entry that spoke to me today. .
October 27, 1990
Sometimes in my darker moments I look at all l’ve done, and all I will do, and ask, What does it add up to?” Such a small and inadequate being I am-the things that I make so few-_the thoughts that l’ve written down so sparse. Other people have done so much more.
Tonight the answer came to me: a life. It adds up to a life. Nothing more, nothing less. I can’t quantify the value of my existence according to the number of pictures made or essays written. What I can do is work hard and live. Live it out.
And listen. My soul knows where it wants to go, but often I’m unwilling to trust the inner voice, to relax and be led. I don’t control my growth. I nurture it and often just get out of the way and let it happen.
I can’t take my pictures or my words with me. But I may take with me what Ibecome.
.
.

A few take aways from my 7 days of ‘flat lays’…
And/or ‘from above’ photos.
.

1	Space - Don’t overcrowd your flatlay. Allow each element room to breathe, creating a peaceful holiday atmosphere. You do not have to cover the entire background. 
	2	Think theme - Craft a cohesive narrative with your props. Every element should contribute to your story.
	3	Spacing between Props - Balance is key. Give each prop its own spotlight while maintaining the overall harmony.
	4	Human Touch - Add life to your flatlay. A simple human element can make your composition more relatable and engaging.
	5	Depth and Layers - Create visual interest by playing with depth and layers. It’s all about drawing the viewer in.
	6	Texture - Incorporate different textures to make your flatlay visually appealing. Think soft knits, linen, rough pine cones, or smooth Christmas baubles.
	7	Details - Pay attention to the small things. A little extra touch can elevate your scene and make it truly special. Frothy cuppa or a hot steaming cup of tea can add that little extra something. 
Bonus tip and my fav. 
	8	Sense of Place - Your flatlay should hint at a wider world. Whether it’s a snowy landscape outside, a lush indoor Christmas tree, or a far-off holiday destination.
. I went deeper into this over on my blog if you’re interested. 
I hope these tips inspire you to create your own festive flatlays this holiday season and beyond. Xx

Ever found yourself pondering over the right words?
Your beautiful moment is captured, but the perfect caption eludes you.
Days, sometimes weeks, pass with your post waiting in drafts for just the right words.
.
Creating captions is an art of its own, blending thoughtfulness with expression.
It’s okay if it sometimes feels challenging; it’s all part of our creative journey.
.
Here are a few practical tips to guide you out of ‘Caption Jail’ so you can get on with sharing your art with the world.
.
Use a Quote or Song Lyric: Sometimes, someone else’s words can perfectly encapsulate what you want to say. Find a quote or a line from a song that resonates with your image or video.
.
Ask a Question: Engage your audience directly. A question can be a great caption by itself and encourages interaction. For instance, “What’s your favorite way to spend the week after Christmas?’
.
Describe the Moment: Sometimes, simplicity is key. Describe what’s happening in the photo or video. This can be a sensory description (what you see, hear, feel) or an emotional one.
.
Tell a Story: Start with a prompt like “So THIS happened...” or “Currently...” or “Lately...” or I’m loving…
The caption does NOT have to relate directly to your photo or video. This can be very freeing for sharing words with a quiet moment.
